<node TEXT="smaller ramp angle means&#xa;more locking" ID="ID_1679141230" CREATED="1681502863438" MODIFIED="1681502878534"/>
<node TEXT="We&#x2019;ll focus on ramp angles for now, this is 85/35. The first number can be seen as &#x201c;Power&#x201d; and second as &#x201c;Coast&#x201d;. A high &#x201c;Power&#x201d; and low &#x201c;Coast&#x201d; will feel easier and more stable to drive." ID="ID_1729197163" CREATED="1681504322202" MODIFIED="1681504328424"/>
</node>
<node TEXT="55 engine braking" FOLDED="true" ID="ID_1685627395" CREATED="1681504619090" MODIFIED="1681504625176">
<node TEXT="With the 1955 cars, engine braking was a crucial technique to learn. As you approach a corner, as well as using the brakes, change down a gear, don&apos;t blip the throttle to match the revs as you might do with later cars, then let your foot off the clutch gently, and you can effectively use your clutch plates as an extra form of braking. For some tracks, (such as Hockenheim &apos;67 when entering the stadium section) you will need to repeat this technique on each downshift to get the car slowed down enough. 1955 car engines had impressive compression ratios, so you could safely use engine braking to slow you down without worrying too much about over-revving the engine and watching your cylinder head become the first satellite in orbit.&#xa;&#xa;In my humble opinion, the GPL 1955 mod is the first mod which really makes it necessary for the driver to take into consideration the limits of the car technology of the time. Learning how to stop a 1955 car is not the same as stopping a 1967 car. If you can learn the difference, and learn the different techniques involved, then you will enjoy the 1955 mod." ID="ID_961844235" CREATED="1681504627100" MODIFIED="1681504644755"/>
</node>
<node TEXT="score example" FOLDED="true" ID="ID_674644331" CREATED="1681504821823" MODIFIED="1681504833157">
<node TEXT="Chose TUE OKR #1,2 compare laptime (driving a lotus 49 from the 67 mod) on the spa67 track vs GPL rank benchmark laptime of 3 minutes, 20 seconds.&#xa;&#xa;I set up a short 3 lap race at the spa67 track vs. AI opponents in F2 cars as follows:&#xa;&#xa;    select the Lotus 49 car&#xa;    examine the replay of a fast lap with a lotus 47 at spa67, where the replay file name is TUE/WP/drive_c/Sierra/GPL/fs_spa67_lotus_32364_60fps.rpy, using both the REPLAY command within GPL and using the replay analyzer. (The replay analyzer is invoked from the TUE directory via ./replay.sh&#xa;    run a standard 15 minute practice vs. the AI&#xa;    When the green button on lower right appears indicating that the race is about to start, select the red button on lower left instead and save the practice session.&#xa;    run ./editRaceLineup.sh in the TUE directory, edit TUE/WP/drive_c/GPL/players/67__Driver/spa67.html, select all AI oppontents have the slower formula 2 (F2) cars, set race length of 3 laps, and make me #1 on the starting grid. Save the modified spa67.html file.&#xa;    Run GPL, selecting the &apos;67 lotus 49 at spa67, and select restore saved practice results.&#xa;&#xa;Note that after a race the spa67.html file is deleted, so be sure to save a copy of this file before the race. Copy that saved file to spa67.html before starting your next race, if you want to continue to use the modified race settings.&#xa;&#xa;Comparing my replay results with fs_spa67_lotus_32364_60fps.rpy showed that while I shifted gears at mostly the same points, I was much slower. I was 100 km/hr slower at the Masta Kink than the car in the fs_spa67_lotus_32364_60fps.rpy replay file!&#xa;&#xa;Complete race results summary files are included.&#xa;&#xa;Note that I also ran the GPLMotec telemetry program via ./twpMonitorTelemetry.sh. The GPLMotec screenshot shows that my tire temperatures are 60-70 degrees C, much lower than the optimum tire temperature of 127 degrees C for the &apos;67 lotus 49 listed in TUE/DOC/GPL cars spreadsheet.xls. This much lower temperature probably reduced tire grip by more than 20%, vis. TUE/DOC/GPL_gripVsTirePressureAndTemp.pdf&#xa;&#xa;MY best laptime was 4 minutes, 17 seconds. Comparing that vs the &apos;67 GPL rank spa67 benchmark time of 3 minutes, 20 seconds, I calculate my score for TUE OKR #1,2 as described in THE/calculatingScore.txt:&#xa;&#xa;gpl rank ratio = (my benchmark time - gpl rank benchmark time) / (gpl rank benchmark time) = (4+17/60-(3+20/60))/(3+20/60)=.285&#xa;&#xa;Thus my TUE score is (1-3*.285)/10=.0145" ID="ID_593369938" CREATED="1681504833206" MODIFIED="1681504846743"/>
</node>
